  "body": "### Component\n\nForge\n\n### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?\n\n- [X] Foundry\n- [X] Foundryup\n\n### What version of Foundry are you on?\n\nforge 0.2.0 (37e4376 2022-07-16T00:12:54.96929664Z)\n\n### What command(s) is the bug in?\n\nforge test\n\n### Operating System\n\nLinux\n\n### Describe the bug\n\nNot sure if this is intended behavior or not. When call `vm.setEvn` within a test, it sets the environment for all currently running tests.\r\n\r\nThis essentially means it is unsafe to run tests that use `env` in parallel. I've tested tests in different files and they  are also not isolated.\r\n\r\nBecause test are not deterministically scheduled this can also lead to non-deterministic test failures, where one case will race another to set & read the env.\r\n\r\nAs a reference, this was found while trying to test `solenv`. To address this, all test cases had to be consolidated: https://github.com/proximacapital/solenv/blob/master/test/Solenv.t.sol#L46\r\n\r\nNot sure if we are expecting devs to regularly be setting and getting env in tests. I could imagine some integration tests using `setFork` would want to read env and may get tripped by this (if any test sets env)?\r\n",
